    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Health Insurance Tax</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Phil Casella letter proposes that everybody's health insurance be made taxable, with revenue to be used to help provide insurance to all</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''There Goes the Surplus'' (editorial, Oct. 27), you criticize a Congressional bill that ''would provide tax deductions for the purchase of health insurance by individuals not covered by their employers.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''There Goes the Surplus'' (editorial, Oct. 27), you criticize a Congressional bill that ''would provide tax deductions for the purchase of health insurance by individuals not covered by their employers.''</p>
        <p>True, this is not a great help to the poor, who can't afford health insurance in any case; but it would help many thousands of self-employed people, most of whom are not rich. And it's fair: millions of people get health benefits from their employers and don't pay taxes on this benefit. This is in effect the same tax deduction ''for the purchase of health insurance'' that you oppose.</p>
        <p>Here's an idea: let's make everybody's health insurance taxable, and use the revenue to help provide insurance to all.</p>
        <p>PHIL CASELLA  Palo Alto, Calif., Oct. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
